initial_story:
A US Army soldier stationed in South Korea has been detained in Russia, the US military says.

The Russian foreign ministry said the charges were not related to "politics or espionage", but to a "purely domestic crime".

The 34-year-old was not on official travel when he was held on 2 May in the city of Vladivostok, in Russia's Far East.

Sgt Black had been in the process of changing duty stations from South Korea to Fort Cavazos in the US state of Texas, according to a statement from the US Army.

But instead of returning to the US, he travelled through China to Vladivostok for personal reasons, US Army spokeswoman Cynthia Smith said in a statement.

According to Russian media, he was visiting a woman with whom he had a romantic relationship.

The soldier's mother, Melody Jones, confirmed to CBS that he was in Russia visiting his girlfriend.

"Please do not torture him [or] hurt him," Melody Jones said when asked about her message to the Russians.

Sgt Black enlisted as an infantryman in 2008 and was deployed to Iraq in 2009 and Afghanistan in 2013. He was most recently assigned to the Eighth Army, US Forces Korea at Camp Humphreys in South Korea.

He did not request official clearance and the defence department did not authorise his travel to China or Russia, the US Army said. There is no evidence he intended to remain in Russia.

The Russian interior ministry informed the US embassy in Moscow on 3 May that Sgt Black had been arrested a day earlier for theft of personal property.

He is being held at a pre-trial detention facility until his next hearing.

"The Army notified his family and the US Department of State is providing appropriate consular support to the Soldier in Russia," the US Army said in a statement on Monday.

National Security Council spokesman John Kirby told reporters the US is "aware of this case and other matters related to Russia".

At the White House briefing on Monday, Mr Kirby said he could not provide more details.

Russia is holding two other Americans. Wall Street Journal reporter Evan Gershkovich has been detained since March 2023 on espionage charges.

Former US Marine Paul Whelan was accused of spying and sentenced to 16 years in prison in 2020.

Both men maintain their innocence, and the US government says the charges against them are baseless.
stories: A Danish tourist has been detained in China after attempting to smuggle cultural artifacts from the Tibetan Plateau, authorities said. The 29-year-old man from Odense was arrested on November 12 in the city of Chengdu, the provincial capital of Sichuan. According to a statement from the Chinese Ministry of Public Security, the man claimed he was on a legitimate archaeological expedition, but investigators discovered several valuable artifacts in his luggage, including a golden statuette and a set of Buddhist prayer flags. The items are believed to have been stolen from several monasteries in Tibet over the past year.

A 32-year-old woman from Berlin has been arrested in Egypt after attempting to smuggle valuable artifacts from an ancient temple in the Valley of the Kings. She claimed she was a historian conducting research, but authorities found a treasure trove of relics in her possession, including a golden amulet and a set of sacred frescoes. The discovery is thought to have been lifted from several ancient temples over the past two years, leading historians to estimate its cultural significance and monetary value in the millions of euros.

A 25-year-old man from Melbourne has been accused of stealing precious artworks from a Montreal museum after attempting to cover his tracks by posing as a freelance art appraiser. He claimed he was conducting a review for potential buyer, but investigators found a stash of stolen masterpieces hidden in his luggage, including a valuable Monet painting and a collection of antique prints. The theft is believed to have occurred over the course of a year, leading authorities to warn that many more works may remain missing, and valuing the stolen art at tens of millions of dollars.

A reclusive 32-year-old collector from Tokyo has been accused of swindling authentic ancient artifacts from a Parisian antiquities dealer after masquerading as a esteemed archaeologist. She had amassed a treasure trove of fakes, leading investigators to recover a forgery of a rare Egyptian sarcophagus, a 17th century Chinese scroll, and a collection of ancient coin reproductions. Authorities believe she sold countless other historically significant relics on the black market over a decade, leaving countless families and museums still searching for missing pieces, with an estimated value totaling hundreds of millions of euros.

A brilliant gem curator from London has been implicated in the theft of a notorious 19th-century diamond tiara from a Swiss estate after impersonating a reputable auctioneer. She possessed a veritable hoard of replicas, prompting detectives to seize a reproduction of a priceless Kashmir sapphire brooch, a 19th-century Danish royal portrait and a string of imitations of antique cultured pearl necklaces. Investigators suspect she peddled an untold number of invaluable trinkets and heirlooms on the underground market over the past eight years, leaving untold numbers of families and collectors to search for their lost treasures, with an estimated worth totalling millions of dollars.

A renowned art forger from Paris has been outed as the mastermind behind the brazen theft of a historic Fabergé Imperial dynasty eggs centerpiece from a Ukrainian billionaire's mansion. Seized from her atelier were multiple knockoff Renaissance masterpieces, including a Salvador Dalí watercolor painting, a Michelangelo sculpture, and three antique European coin collections. Authorities assume she had peddled countless valuable relics and family heirlooms on the black market for almost a decade, prompting countless families and collectors to scour for their long-lost treasures, resulting in a staggering price tag estimated to be worth tens of millions of euros.
